inona County, Minnesota|Winona]]\n|61\n|10\n|-\n|[[Wright County, Minnesota|Wright]]\n|25\n|1\n|-\n|[[Yellow Medicine County, Minnesota|Yellow Medicine]]\n|3\n|0\n|-\n|'''Total'''\n|'''2,470'''\n|'''143'''\n|}\n\n==Responses==\n===State government===\n[[File:Lake Area Quick Lube sign in White Bear Lake, Minnesota.jpg|thumb|\"Corona Hours\" sign at the Lake Area Quick Lube in White Bear Lake, Minnesota- Auto Repair and Maintenance shops are considered \"essential businesses\"]]\nOn March 10, Minnesota Governor Tim Walz signed a bill to dedicate $20.8 million to state coronavirus response.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 13, Governor Walz declared a peacetime state of emergency.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn March 15, Governor Walz authorized the temporary closing of all public K-12 schools from March 18 until at least March 27.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> On March 25, this closure was extended to May 4.\n\nOn March 16, the Minnesota legislature began scaling back operations and meeting on an on-call basis.<ref name=\":5\" /> Governor Walz also ordered the closure of public places, including all: restaurants, bars, coffee shops, gyms, theaters, breweries, ski resorts, and other public places until at least March 27. Bars and restaurants in the state were closed only to dine-in customers; the businesses were allowed to continue to serve customers by take-out or delivery orders.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/16/walz-covid19-bar-restaurant-closure-and-unemployment-help |title=Walz temporarily closes bars, restaurants and gyms to curb COVID-19 spread |last=MPR Staff |website=Minnesota Public Radio |access-date=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317231710/https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/16/walz-covid19-bar-restaurant-closure-and-unemployment-help |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 25, this order was extended until May 1.\n\nOn March 25, Governor Walz issued a [[stay-at-home order]], claiming that at this point it was too late to \"flatten the curve\" with relation to new cases. The stay-at-home order required Minnesotans to restrict activity outside the home from 11:59&nbsp;p.m. on March 27 until 5 p.m. on April 10.<ref>{{cite news\n| date = March 25, 2020\n| title = Minnesota Press Conference: COVID-19 Stay at Home Order\n| url = https://www.wdio.com/duluth-minnesota-news/minnesota-governor-walz-conference-stay-at-home-order/5684276/\n| accessdate = March 25, 2020\n}}</ref> While the order did continue the closure of bars, restaurants, movie theaters, hair salons, and other \"non-essential\" locations, the majority of workplaces still remained open for some employees in order to provide \"essential services.\" Some of the places deemed \"essential\" included mechanics (bike and auto), chiropractors, grocery stores, any store that sold food or drink including bakeries, butcher shops, liquor stores and even popcorn shops. Many restaurants continued to stay open for take-out and curbside pickup. Many retail stores also maintained a skeleton staff and offered curbside pickup, or only allowed a few people in the store at one time.<ref>{{cite web |title=Minnesota Critical Businesses List |url=https://mn.gov/deed/assets/naics-critical-list_tcm1045-424829.pdf |website=Minnesota Department of Employment and Economic Development |publisher=Government of Minnesota |accessdate=30 March 2020 |date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Orenstein |first1=Walker |title=Who and what is and isn't covered by Minnesota's new 'Stay-at-Home' order |url=https://www.minnpost.com/state-government/2020/03/who-and-what-is-and-isnt-covered-by-minnesotas-new-stay-at-home-order/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |publisher=Minnpost.com |date=25 March 2020 |location=Minneapolis, Minnesota}}</ref>\n\n===City governments===\nOn March 14, [[St. Paul, MN|St. Paul]] Mayor [[Melvin Carter (politician)|Melvin Carter]] declared a State of Local Emergency. The city will no longer be issuing any new permits for gatherings of 50 or more people. He also requested that [[Ramsey County, MN|Ramsey County]] police suspend all evictions. The [[St. Paul Public Library]], St. Paul Schools, and all parks and recreation centers including the [[Como Zoo]] were also closed from March 16 through March 27.<ref name=\"schools\" />\n\nIn March, the City of [[Red Wing, Minnesota]] suspended city facilities and shut down the city library due to concerns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://red-wing.org/975/Coronavirus-COVID-19|title=COV-19|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> in March 31, Red Wing reported its first cases at a corrections facility<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.postbulletin.com/life/health/first-covid-19-cases-reported-minnesota-correctional-facilities-including-red-wing/article_9c4af926-7353-11ea-bba3-fbcabfed2e7a.html|title=First COVID-19 cases reported Minnesota correctional facilities, including Red Wing|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of the state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12. [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]] on that date, and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota Timberwolves]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>  In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Minnesota Wild season|Minnesota Wild]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] canceled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> The 2020 [[NCAA Division I Wrestling Championships]] were scheduled for March 19\u201321 at [[Minneapolis|Minneapolis']] [[U.S. Bank Stadium]]. By March 11, the NCAA had announced the championship would continue, but none of the anticipated 100,000 fans would be allowed to attend.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shipley |first1=John |title=NCAA decision means empty U.S. Bank Stadium for wrestling championship |url=https://www.twincities.com/2020/03/11/ncaa-decision-means-u-s-bank-stadium-will-be-empty-for-wrestling-championships/ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |publisher=St. Paul Pioneer Press |date=11 March 2020 |location=St. Paul, Minnesota}}</ref> The following day the NCAA canceled all spring championships.\n\nOn March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 21, the [[Brainerd, Minnesota|Brainerd]] [[Jaycees]] announced the cancelation of the [[Run for the Lakes Marathon]] and all other races taking place over the marathon weekend, which was scheduled for April 24\u201325. The [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] ended the 11-year streak of consecutive marathon runnings.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bieser |first1=Toni |title=Brainerd Jaycees Run the Lakes Press Release |url=https://scontent-msp1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/90414801_2772600102787521_4170424978266652672_n.jpg?_nc_cat=107&_nc_sid=110474&_nc_oc=AQkQLcDykFyXA__1XHnQefsaEMA6j_WgN0VuN1eQGAby5JFPCtLBT2gveOCCN-O7jP4&_nc_ht=scontent-msp1-1.xx&oh=6ff9b8f13d6c0ada3a7f4ae9797ea08e&oe=5EA19C8A |website=Facebook.com |publisher=Brainerd Jaycees |accessdate=25 March 2020 |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n[[Grandma's Marathon]] was held annually for 43 years, making it one of the oldest continually-run marathons in the country. But on March 31, the staff announced that the June 16, 2020, race was canceled due to concerns of spreading [[SARS-CoV-2]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galioto |first1=Katie |title=Grandma's Marathon canceled due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.startribune.com/grandma-s-marathon-canceled-due-to-covid-19/569250322/ |accessdate=31 March 2020 |publisher=Star Tribune |date=31 March 2020 |location=Minneapolis, Minnesota}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, race officials decided to cancel the [[Lake Wobegon Trail Marathon]] for the first time since the race began in 2008. The race runs on the state trail from [[Holdingford, Minnesota]], to [[St. Joseph, Minnesota]].\n<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mozey |first1=Brian |title=Lake Wobegon Trail Marathon cancelled due to COVID-19; replaced by virtual race |url=https://www.sctimes.com/story/sports/2020/04/02/lake-wobegon-trail-marathon-cancelled-due-covid-19-virtual-race/5118285002/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |agency=USA Today |publisher=St. Cloud Times |date=2 April 2020 |location=St. Cloud, Minnesota}}</ref>\n\nBy April 6, nearly 1,000 people in the state had contracted [[COVID-19]], and the [[Rochester, Minnesota]]-based [[Med City Marathon]] race organizers decided to postpone their race weekend from May 23\u201324 to September 4\u20135.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jahns |first1=Isaac |title=Med City Marathon moved to September |url=https://www.medcitybeat.com/news-blog/2020/med-city-marathon-moved-to-september |accessdate=6 April 2020 |publisher=MedCity Beat |date=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Bongers |first1=Mark |title=2020 Final Stretch Events \u2013 Med City Marathon presented by Active PT |url=https://www.medcitymarathon.com/images/Med_City_date_rescheduled.pdf |website=Medcitymarathon.com |accessdate=6 April 2020 |location=Rochester, Minnesota |format=PDF |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Additional Diagrams and Images==\n<gallery>\nfile:COVID-19 Case Status in Minnesota.svg|Status of cases beginning 14 April 2020\n</gallery>\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Minnesota}}\n* [https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/index.html Coronavirus information] from the [[Minnesota Department of Health]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Minnesota]]\n[[Category:2020 in Minnesota|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Health in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Scrampea", "label": "safe", "comment": "update last access date for MN-official data", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Minnesota"}
{"title_page": "Coral Sea", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Short description|A marginal sea of the South Pacific off the northeast coast of Australia}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox sea\n| name = Coral Sea\n| image = Coral Sea map.png\n| caption = \n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = \n| coords = {{coord|18|S|158|E|type:waterbody_scale:10000000|display=inline,title}}\n| type = [[Sea]]\n| inflow = \n| outflow = \n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = [[Australia]], [[New Caledonia]] ([[France]]), [[Papua New Guinea]], [[Solomon Islands]], [[Vanuatu]]\n| length = \n| width = \n| area = {{convert|4791000|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth = {{convert|2394|m|abbr=on}}\n| max-depth = {{convert|9140|m|abbr=on}}\n| volume = {{convert|11470000|km3|acre.ft|abbr=on}}\n| frozen = \n| reference = <ref name=bse>[http://bse.sci-lib.com/article064525.html Coral Sea], [[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]] (in Russian)</ref><ref name=brit>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/137118/Coral-Sea Coral Sea], Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica on-line</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Coral Sea''' ({{Lang-fr|Mer de Corail}}) is a [[marginal sea]] of the [[Pacific Ocean|South Pacific]] off the northeast coast of [[Australia]], and classified as an [[Interim Biogeographic Regionalisation for Australia|interim Australian]] [[bioregion]]. The Coral Sea extends {{convert|2,000|km}} down the Australian northeast coast. The sea was the location for the [[Battle of the Coral Sea]], a major confrontation during [[World War II]] between the navies of the Empire of Japan, and the United States and Australia.\n\nThe water contains numerous islands and [[coral reef|reef]]s, as well as the world's largest reef system, the [[Great Barrier Reef]] (GBR), which was declared a [[World Heritage Site]] by [[UNESCO]] in 1981. All previous [[oil exploration]] projects were terminated at the GBR in 1975, and fishing is restricted in many areas. The reefs and islands of the Coral Water are particularly rich in birds and aquatic life and are a popular tourist destination, both nationally and internationally.\n\n==Geography==\nIt is bounded in the west by the east coast of [[Queensland]], thereby including the [[Great Barrier Reef]], in the east by [[Vanuatu]] (formerly the [[New Hebrides]]) and by [[New Caledonia]], and in the northeast approximately by the southern extremity of the [[Solomon Islands]]. In the northwest, it reaches to the south coast of eastern [[New Guinea]], thereby including the [[Gulf of Papua]]. It merges with the [[Tasman Sea]] in the south, with the [[Solomon Sea]] in the north and with the Pacific Ocean in the east. On the west, it is bounded by the mainland coast of [[Queensland]], and in the northwest, it connects with the [[Arafura Sea]] through the [[Torres Strait]].<ref name=brit/>\n\nThe water is characterised by its warm and stable climate{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}, with frequent rains and [[tropical cyclone]]s\n\n==Extent==\n[[File:Coral Sea Islands.png|thumb|A map of the Coral Sea Islands]]\nWhile the [[Great Barrier Reef]] with its islands and cays belong to Queensland, most reefs and islets west of it are part of the [[Coral Sea Islands Territory]]. In addition, some islands west of and belonging to [[New Caledonia]] are also part of the Coral Sea Islands in a geographical sense, such as the [[Chesterfield Islands]] and [[Bellona Reefs]].\n\nThe [[International Hydrographic Organization]] defines the limits of the Coral Water as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iho.int/iho_pubs/standard/S-23/S-23_Ed3_1953_EN.pdf|title=Limits of Oceans and Seas, 3rd edition|year=1953|publisher=[[International Hydrographic Organization]]|page=37|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref>\n<blockquote>\n''On the North.'' The South coast of [[New Guinea]] from the entrance to the [[Bensbach River]] (141\u00b001'E) to Gadogadoa Island near its Southeastern extreme ({{coord|10|38|S|150|34|E|display=inline}}), down this meridian to the 100 fathom line and thence along the Southern edges of Uluma Reef and those extending to the Eastward as far as the Southeast point of Lawik Reef ({{coord|11|43.5|S|153|56.5|E|display=inline}}) off Tagula Island, thence a line to the Southern extreme of [[Rennell Island]] ([[Solomon Islands]]) and from its Eastern point to Cape Surville, the Eastern extreme of San Cristobal Island <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Makira]]<nowiki>]</nowiki>, [[Solomon Islands|Solomons]]; thence through [[Nalongo and Nupani|Nupani Island]], the Northwestern of the [[Santa Cruz Islands]] ({{coord|10|04.5|S|165|40.5|E|display=inline}}) to the Northernmost Island of the [[Duff Islands]] ({{coord|9|48.5|S|167|06|E|display=inline}}).\n\n''On the Northeast.'' From the Northernmost island of the Duff Islands, through these islands to their Southeastern extreme, thence a line to M\u00e9r\u00e9 Lava, [[Vanuatu]] Islands({{coord|14|25|S|163|03|E|display=inline}}) and down the Eastern coasts of the islands of this Group to [[Anatom]] Island ({{coord|20|11|S|169|51|E|display=inline}}) in such a way that all the islands of these Groups, and the straits separating them, are included in the Coral water.\n\n''On the Southeast.'' A line from the Southeastern extreme of Anatom Island to Nokanhoui (reefs) ({{coord|22|46|S|167|34|E|display=inline}}) off the Southeast extreme of [[New Caledonia]], thence through the East point of [[Middleton Reef]] to the Eastern extreme of [[Elizabeth Reef]] ({{coord|29|55|S|159|02|E|display=inline}}) and down this meridian to [[30th parallel south|Latitude 30\u00b0 South]].\n\n''On the South.'' The parallel of 30\u00b0 South to the Australian coast.\n\n''On the West.'' The Eastern limit of the [[Arafura Sea]] [The entrance to the [[Bensbach River]] (141\u00b001'E), and thence a line to the Northwest extreme of [[Cape York Peninsula|York Peninsula]], Australia ({{coord|11|05|S|142|03|E|display=inline}})] and the East Coast of Australia as far south as Latitude 30\u00b0 South.\n</blockquote>\n\n==Geology==\nThe Coral water [[Oceanic basin|basin]] was formed between 58 million and 48 million years ago when the Queensland continental shelf was uplifted, forming the [[Great Dividing Range]], and continental blocks subsided at the same time.<ref>Hopley, p. 19</ref> The water has been an important source of coral for the Great Barrier Reef, both during its formation and after [[sea level change|sea level lowering]].<ref>Hopley, p. 27</ref>\n\nThe geological formation processes are still proceeding, as partly evidenced by the [[seismic activity]]. Several hundred earthquakes with the [[Richter magnitude scale|magnitude]] between 2 and 6 were recorded in the period 1866\u20132000 along the Queensland coast and in the Coral water.<ref>Hopley, pp. 33\u201334</ref> On 2 April 2007, the Solomon Islands were struck by a [[2007 Solomon Islands earthquake and tsunami|major earthquake]] followed by a several metres tall [[tsunami]]. The epicentre of this magnitude 8.1 earthquake was {{convert|349|km|mi|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Honiara]], at a depth of {{convert|10|km|mi}}.<ref>[http://www.breakinglegalnews.com/entry/Solomon-Islands-earthquake-and-tsunami \"Solomon Islands earthquake and tsunami\"], Breaking Legal News \u2013 International, 4 March 2007</ref> It was followed by more than 44 aftershocks of a magnitude 5.0 or greater. The resulting tsunami killed at least 52 people and destroyed more than 900 homes.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6520461.stm \"Aid reaches tsunami-hit Solomons\"], ''BBC News'', 2007-04-03</ref>\n\nThe water received its name because of its numerous coral formations. They include the GBR, which extends about {{convert|2000|km|mi|abbr=on}} along the northeast coast of Australia and includes approximately 2,900 individual reefs<ref name=britGBR>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/242906/Great-Barrier-Reef Great Barrier Reef], Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica on-line</ref> and 1000 islands.<ref>Hopley, pp. 1, 26</ref> The [[Chesterfield Islands]] and [[Lihou Reef National Nature Reserve|Lihou Reef]] are the largest [[atoll]]s of the Coral water.\n\n==Hydrology==\n[[File:East Australian Current.jpg|thumb|left|Thermal profile of the East Australian Current]]\nMajor Coral water currents form a counter-clockwise gyro which includes the [[East Australian Current]]. It brings warm nutrient-poor waters from the Coral water down the east coast of Australia to the cool waters of the Tasman waters. This current is the strongest along the Australian coasts and transforms 30 million m<sup>3</sup>/s of water within a flow band of about 100 kilometres wide and 500 metres deep. The current is strongest around February and weakest around August.<ref>[http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/NaturalHazards/view.php?id=15366 East Australian Current], NASA</ref>\n\nThe major river flowing into the sea is the [[Burdekin River]], which has its delta southeast of [[Townsville]]. Owing to the seasonal and annual variations in occurrence of cyclones and in precipitation (typically between 200 and 1600 mm/year), its annual discharge can vary more than 10 times between the two succeeding years. In particular, in the period 1920\u20131999, the average flow rate near the delta was below 1000 m<sup>3</sup>/s in 1923, 1931, 1939, 1969, 1982, 1985, 1987, 1993 and 1995; it was above 25,000 m<sup>3</sup>/s in 1927, 1940, 1946, 1950, 1951, 1959, 1968, 1972, 1974 and 1991, and reached about 40,000 m<sup>3</sup>/s in 1946.<ref>Susan B. Marriott, Jan Alexander [https://books.google.com/books?id=jB2CKLZc2eMC&pg=PA31 Floodplains: interdisciplinary approaches], Geological Society, 1999 {{ISBN|1-86239-050-9}} p. 31</ref> This irregularity results in concomitant fluctuations of the sea water composition near the river delta.\n\nThe surface water temperature varies on the south of the sea from 19 \u00b0C in August to 24 \u00b0C in February. It is rather warm and stable at 27\u201328 \u00b0\u0421 in the north all through the year. Water salinity is 34.5\u201335.5\u2030 (parts per thousand).<ref name=bse/> The water is mostly very clear, with the visibility of about 30 metres (100 ft) near the reefs.<ref name=britGBR/>\n\n==Climate==\n[[File:Cyclone Larry 19 mar 2006 0025Z.jpg|thumb|[[Cyclone Larry|Tropical Cyclone Larry]] over the Great Barrier Reef, 19 March 2006]]\nThe sea has a subtropical climate and is frequently hit by [[tropical cyclone]]s, especially between January and April.<ref name=brit/> This range extends to November\u2013May in the areas south to 10\u00b0S. Between 1969 and 1997, the GBR experienced 80 cyclones, 90% which were of [[Saffir\u2013Simpson Hurricane Scale|category]] 1 or 2 (winds 17\u201333 m/s, central pressure 970\u20131000 hPa) and only 10% of category 3 (winds >33 m/s, pressure <970 hPa). The cyclone frequency decreased between 1997 and 2005 to 1.5 per year (12 in total).<ref name=h96>Hopley, p. 96</ref>\n\nAnnual rainfall typically ranges between 1,000 and 3,000 mm depending on the area. Most rains fall between December and March, in bursts of 30\u201360 days.<ref name=h96/> The number of clear days per year varies approximately between 80 and 125, and the typical temperature variation through the year are 18\u201327 \u00b0C.<ref name=meteo>[http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/data/ Climate Data Online], Australian Bureau of Meteorology</ref>\n\n[[global warming|Climate change]] made it 175 times more likely that the surface waters of the Coral Sea would reach the record-breaking temperatures March 2016 that bleached reefs, modeling analysis showed.<ref>{{cite web|author=John Upton |title=Climate Change is 'Devastating' The Great Barrier Reef |url=http://www.climatecentral.org/news/climate-change-devastating-great-barrier-reef--20295 |accessdate=2016-06-01}}</ref>\n\n===Winds===\nWinds in the Coral Sea can be classified by season, [[longitude]] and [[latitude]]. Southeasterly [[trade wind]]s dominate through all sea areas and all seasons, especially between 20\u00b0S and 25\u00b0S, west of the meridian of 155\u00b0E. However, between September and December they change to northerly and northwesterly winds in this region, and the direction is mostly southwestern in May\u2013August. West of 155\u00b0E, [[gale]]s are common between January and August and are less frequent in September\u2013December.<ref name=w/>\n\nIn January, the northwest [[monsoon]] may occur between the parallels of 15\u00b0S and 20\u00b0S, west of the 150\u00b0E meridian. Gales are rare in this region most of the year except for June\u2013August, when strong southeasterly winds occur a few days per month.<ref name=w/>\n\nThe southeasterly trades are also strong north of 15\u00b0S between March and November. They weaken and often change to westerly winds in December and to northerly and northwesterly winds in January\nand February.<ref name=w>[http://permanent.access.gpo.gov/websites/pollux/pollux.nss.nima.mil/NAV_PUBS/SD/pub127/127sec06.pdf Australia\u2014Coral Sea\u2014Islands and Dangers], p. 131</ref>\n\n==Flora==\nThe Australian shore of the Coral Sea is mostly composed of sand. The GBR is too far away to provide significant coral deposits, but it effectively screens the coast from the ocean waves. As a result, most land vegetation spreads down to the sea,<ref>Jonathan D. Sauer [https://books.google.com/books?id=EimtEIqbuGYC&pg=PA53 Cayman Islands seashore vegetation: a study in comparative biogeography], University of California Press, 1982 {{ISBN|0520096568}} pp. 47, 53</ref> and the coastal waters are rich in underwater vegetation, such as [[green algae]].<ref>Alan R. Longhurst [https://books.google.com/books?id=MFHK18F5aCsC&pg=PA332 Ecological Geography of the Sea], Academic Press, 1998 {{ISBN|0-12-455559-4}} pp. 331\u2013332</ref> The most common [[genus|genera]] of seagrasses are ''[[Halophila]]'' and ''[[Halodule]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/seagrasses |year=2005 |title=Environmental Status: Seagrasses |work=The State of the Great Barrier Reef Report \u2013 latest updates |accessdate=23 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323172107/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/seagrasses |archivedate=23 March 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe islands of the GBR contain more than 2,000 plant species, and three of these are [[Endemism|endemic]]. The northern islands have 300\u2013350 plant species which tend to be woody, whereas the southern islands have 200 which are more herbaceous; the Whitsunday region is the most diverse, supporting 1,141 species. The plants are spread by birds.<ref name=\"Flora and Fauna 5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora/appendix_05.html|title=Appendix 5- Island Flora and Fauna |year=2000|work=Fauna and Flora of the Great Barrier Reef World Heritage Area|accessdate=13 September 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070831160817/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora/appendix_05.html|archivedate=31 August 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Fauna==\n[[File:Coral Outcrop Flynn Reef.jpg|thumb|Corals on Flynn Reef near [[Cairns]]]]\n[[File:Crown of Thorns-jonhanson.jpg|thumb|Crown-of-thorns starfish]]\n[[File:Christmas Tree Worm.jpg|thumb|Christmas tree worm (''[[Spirobranchus giganteus]]'') in [[Porites]] coral. Admiralty, Osprey Reef]]\n[[File:Laticauda colubrina (Wakatobi).jpg|thumb|A banded [[Laticauda|sea krait]] ''Laticauda colubrina'']]\n\nThe sea hosts numerous species of [[Sea anemone|anemones]], [[sponge]]s, worms (e.g. ''[[Spirobranchus giganteus]]'' shown in the photograph), [[Gastropoda|gastropods]], [[lobster]]s, [[crayfish]], [[prawn]]s and crabs. [[Red algae]] ''[[Lithothamnion]]'' and ''[[Porolithon]]'' colour many coral reefs purple-red and the [[green alga]] ''[[Halimeda]]'' is found throughout the sea. The coastal plants consisting of only about 30\u201340 species, and [[mangrove]]s occur in the northern part of the sea.<ref name=britGBR/> Four hundred coral species, both [[hard coral]]s and [[soft coral]]s inhabit the reefs.<ref name=\"CRC species\"/> The majority of these spawn [[gamete]]s, breeding in [[mass spawning]] events that are triggered by the rising sea temperatures of spring and summer, the lunar cycle, and the diurnal cycle. Reefs in the inner GBR spawn during the week after the full moon in October, while the outer reefs spawn in November and December.<ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority |year=2006 |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/8879/Fact_Sheet_20_Coral_Spawning.pdf |title=Information Fact Sheets No. 20 Coral Spawning |format=PDF |accessdate=27 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704074131/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/8879/Fact_Sheet_20_Coral_Spawning.pdf |archivedate=4 July 2009 }}</ref> Its common soft corals belong to 36 genera.<ref>{{cite web |author=Australian Institute of Marine Science |year=2002 |url=http://www.aims.gov.au/pages/research/soft-corals/soft-corals00.html|title=Soft coral atlas of the Great Barrier Reef|accessdate=27 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070406051711/http://www.aims.gov.au/pages/research/soft-corals/soft-corals00.html |archivedate=6 April 2007}}</ref> There are more than 1500 [[List of fishes of the Coral Sea|fish species]] in the reef systems.<ref>C.Michael Hogan. 2011. [http://www.eoearth.org/article/Coral_Sea?topic=49523 ''Coral Sea''. Encyclopedia of Earth. Eds. P.Saundry & C.J.Cleveland. National Council for Science and the Environment. Washington DC]</ref> Five hundred species of marine algae or [[seaweed]] live on the reef,<ref name=\"CRC species\"/> including thirteen species of the genus ''[[Halimeda]]'', which deposit [[calcareous]] mounds up to {{convert|100|m|yd}} wide, creating mini-[[ecosystem]]s on their surface which have been compared to [[rainforest]] cover.<ref>Hopley, p. 185</ref>\n\nCrown-of-thorns starfish (''[[Acanthaster planci]]'') is the major predator of the reefs, as it preys upon [[coral polyp]]s by climbing onto them, [[wiktionary:extrude|extruding]] its stomach over them, and releasing [[digestive enzyme]]s to absorb the liquefied tissue. An individual adult can eat up to 6 m<sup>2</sup> of reef per year.<ref>{{cite web|author=Pierre Madl|title=Marine Biology I \u2013 Acanthaster planci| url=http://biophysics.sbg.ac.at/planci/planci.htm| accessdate=2006-08-28}}</ref> In 2000, an outbreak<ref>The CRC Reef Research Centre defines an outbreak as when there are more than 30 adult starfish in an area of one hectare. {{cite web|author=CRC Reef Research Centre|title=Managing crown-of-thorns starfish outbreaks|url=http://www.reef.crc.org.au/discover/plantsanimals/cots/cotsmanage.html|accessdate=2006-10-18|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002033140/http://www.reef.crc.org.au//discover/plantsanimals/cots/cotsmanage.html|archivedate=2 October 2006|df=dmy-all}} (PDF)</ref> of crown-of-thorns starfish contributed to a loss of 66% of live coral cover on sampled reefs.<ref name=\"cots 1999-2000\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reef.crc.org.au/publications/techreport/techrept32.htm|title=Crc Reef Research Centre Technical Report No. 32 \u2013 Crown-of-thorns starfish(Acanthaster planci) in the central GBR region. Results of fine-scale surveys conducted in 1999\u20132000.|accessdate=2007-06-07|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070829092853/http://www.reef.crc.org.au/publications/techreport/techrept32.htm|archivedate=29 August 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Changes in water quality and [[overfishing]] of natural predators, such as the [[Triton (mollusk)|giant Triton]], may have contributed to an increase in the number of crown-of-thorns starfish.<ref>{{cite web|author=CRC Reef Research Centre |title=Crown-of-thorns starfish on the Great Barrier Reef |url=http://www.reef.crc.org.au/publications/brochures/COTS_web_Nov2003.pdf |accessdate=2006-08-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060826192429/http://www.reef.crc.org.au//publications/brochures/COTS_web_Nov2003.pdf |archivedate=26 August 2006 |df=dmy }} (PDF)</ref>\n\nThere are at least 30 species of whales, dolphins, and [[porpoises]], including the [[dwarf minke whale]], [[Indo-Pacific humpback dolphin]], [[humpback whale]] and [[dugong]]s.<ref name=\"CRC species\">{{cite web|author=CRC Reef Research Centre Ltd |title=Reef facts: Plants and Animals on the Great Barrier Reef |url=http://www.reef.crc.org.au/discover/plantsanimals/facts_plantanimal.htm |accessdate=14 July 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060821194423/http://www.reef.crc.org.au/discover/plantsanimals/facts_plantanimal.htm |archivedate=21 August 2006 |df=dmy}}</ref><ref name=\"GBRMPA Fauna and Flora\">{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority|year=2000 |title=Fauna and Flora of the Great Barrier Reef World Heritage Area|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora |accessdate=24 November 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061014182747/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora |archivedate=14 October 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/marine_mammals |year=2004 |title=Environmental Status: Marine Mammals |work=The State of the Great Barrier Reef Report \u2013 latest updates |accessdate=13 March 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619132323/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/marine_mammals |archivedate=19 June 2010}}</ref> Six species of [[sea turtle]]s breed on the GBR \u2013 the [[green sea turtle]], [[leatherback sea turtle]], [[hawksbill turtle]], [[loggerhead sea turtle]], [[flatback turtle]] and the [[olive ridley]].<ref name=\"rap turtle dugong\">{{cite book |last= Dobbs |first= Kirstin |title= Marine turtle and dugong habitats in the Great Barrier Reef Marine Park used to implement biophysical operational principles for the Representative Areas Program |publisher=Great Barrier Marine Park Authority |year= 2007 |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/18799/rap_turtle_and_dugong_bop.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704064222/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/18799/rap_turtle_and_dugong_bop.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2009-07-04}}</ref>\n\nMore than 200 species of birds (including 22 species of seabirds and 32 species of shorebirds) visit, nest or roost on the islands and reefs,<ref>Hopley, pp. 450\u2013451</ref> including the [[white-bellied sea eagle]] and [[roseate tern]].<ref name=\"CRC species\"/> Most nesting sites are on islands in the northern and southern regions of the GBR, with 1.4\u20131.7 million birds using the sites to breed.<ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/seabirds/ |title=Environmental status: birds |work=The State of the Great Barrier Reef Report \u2013 latest updates |accessdate=23 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090613210510/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/seabirds/ |archivedate=13 June 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/seabirds/condition |title=Environmental status: birds Condition |work=The State of the Great Barrier Reef Report \u2013 latest updates |accessdate=23 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100416181445/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/seabirds/condition |archivedate=16 April 2010 }}</ref>\n\nSeventeen species of [[sea snake]], including ''[[Laticauda colubrina]]''<ref>[http://reptile-database.reptarium.cz/species.php?genus=Laticauda&species=colubrina Laticauda colubrina (SCHNEIDER, 1799)], The Reptile Database</ref> (pictured), live on the GBR in warm waters up to {{convert|50|m|ft}} deep and are more common in the southern than in the northern section; none of them are endemic or endangered.<ref name=\"Flora and Fauna 2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora/appendix_02.html |year=2000 |title=Appendix 2 \u2013 Listed Marine Species |work=Fauna and Flora of the Great Barrier Reef World Heritage Area |accessdate=23 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100326152229/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora/appendix_02.html |archivedate=26 March 2010 }}</ref> The venom of many of these snakes is highly toxic; for example, ''[[Aipysurus duboisii]]'' is regarded as the world's most venomous sea snake.<ref>P. Gopalakrishnakone [https://books.google.com/books?id=i2yTrfdnnq8C&pg=PA98 Sea snake toxinology], NUS Press, 1994, {{ISBN|9971-69-193-0}} p. 98</ref><ref>Harold Heatwole [https://books.google.com/books?id=80ERtB6qgGgC&pg=PT127 Sea Snakes], UNSW Press, 1999, {{ISBN|0-86840-776-3}} p. 115</ref><ref>Steve Backshall [https://books.google.com/books?id=qOyV7KnJRCYC&pg=PA155 Steve Backshall's venom: poisonous animals in the natural world], New Holland Publishers, 2007, {{ISBN|1-84537-734-6}} p. 155</ref>\n\nThere are more than 1,500 [[List of fishes of the Coral Sea|fish species]], including the clownfish ([[Amphiprioninae]]), red bass (''[[Lutjanus bohar]]''), red-throat emperor (''[[Lethrinus miniatus]]''), [[coral trout]] (''[[Plectropomus leopardus]]'') and several species of snapper ([[Lutjanidae]]).<ref name=\"CRC species\"/> Forty-nine species [[Reproductive synchrony|mass spawn]] and eighty-four other species spawn elsewhere in their range.<ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/key_issues/fisheries/spawning_sites|title=Fish Spawning Aggregation Sites on the Great Barrier Reef|accessdate=14 March 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216133142/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/key_issues/fisheries/spawning_sites|archivedate=16 December 2008}}</ref> With a maximum total length of 0.84 cm (0.33 in), ''[[Schindleria brevipinguis]]'', which is native to the GBR and Osprey Reef, is one of the smallest known fish and vertebrate.<ref>W. Watson and H.J. Walker Jr, [http://www.amonline.net.au/pdf/publications/1429_complete.pdf ''The World\u2019s Smallest Vertebrate, Schindleria brevipinguis, A New Paedomorphic Species in the Family Schindleriidae (Perciformes: Gobioidei)''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080808034959/http://www.amonline.net.au/pdf/publications/1429_complete.pdf |date=8 August 2008 }} Records of the Australian Museum (2004) Vol. 56: 139\u2013142. However, it was claimed later (2006) that ''[[Paedocypris progenetica]]'' is the smallest fish and vertebrate.</ref> There are at least 330 species of [[ascidian]]s on the reef system with the diameter of {{convert|1|-|10|cm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}}. Between 300 and 500 species of [[bryozoan]]s live on the reef.<ref name=\"Flora and Fauna 4\"/>\n\n[[Saltwater crocodile]]s live in [[mangrove]] and [[salt marsh]]es on the coast.<ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority |year=2005 |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/marine_reptiles |title=Environmental Status: Marine Reptiles |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701120436/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/marine_reptiles |archivedate=1 July 2010 }}</ref> Around 125 species of [[shark]], [[stingray]], [[Skate (fish)|skate]]s or [[chimaera]] live on the GBR,<ref name=\"Flora and Fauna 4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora/appendix_04.html|title=Appendix 4- Other species of conservation concern |year=2000|work=Fauna and Flora of the Great Barrier Reef World Heritage Area|accessdate=13 September 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070831155453/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora/appendix_04.html|archivedate=31 August 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/sharks_rays|title=Environmental Status: Sharks and rays|work=The State of the Great Barrier Reef Report \u2013 latest updates|accessdate=23 May 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070329002717/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/sharks_rays|archivedate=29 March 2007}}</ref> in addition to about 5,000 species of [[mollusc]]. The latter include the [[giant clam]] and various [[nudibranch]]s and [[cone snail]]s.<ref name=\"CRC species\"/>\n\nOne study of 443 individual sharks gives the following distribution of their species on the Australian side of the Coral Sea: grey reef shark (''[[Carcharhinus amblyrhynchos]]'', 69%), whitetip reef shark (''[[Triaenodon obesus]]'', 21%), silvertip shark (''[[Carcharhinus albimarginatus]]'', 10%), tiger shark (''[[Galeocerdo cuvier]]'', <1%) and great hammerhead (''[[Sphyrna mokarran]]'', <1%). The interaction rate (free diving) at the Coral Sea reefs ranged from a few to 26 sharks per\nhour.<ref>Australian Underwater Federation. [http://www.auf-spearfishing.com.au/Documentation/Coral%20Sea%20Shark%20Report%202008-7.pdf \"Community monitoring of reef sharks in the Coral Sea and Great Barrier Reef, Australia\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080627115546/http://www.auf-spearfishing.com.au/Documentation/Coral%20Sea%20Shark%20Report%202008-7.pdf |date=27 June 2008 }} (2008)</ref> The rare ''[[Etmopterus dislineatus]]'' shark species is endemic to the central part of the Coral Sea. It has been observed at depths of 590\u2013700 m on or near the [[continental slope]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=izASW0ydfVAC&pg=PA374 Deep Sea 2003: conference on the governance and management of deep-sea fisheries], Food & Agriculture Org., 2006 {{ISBN|92-5-105457-6}} p. 374</ref>\n\n==Human activities==\nThe coastal areas of the Coral Sea were populated at least 40,000 years ago by prehistoric people descending through the northern islands. Those Aboriginal tribes have been dispersed and nowadays only about 70 groups live in the area around the GBR.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090912175845/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0012/41241/Traditional_Use.pdf Traditional Use], Great Barrier Reef Outlook Report 2009</ref>\n\nThe sea was the location for the [[Battle of the Coral Sea]], a major confrontation during [[World War II]] between the navies of the [[Empire of Japan]], and the United States and Australia. An example is the wreckage of the ''[[USS Lexington (CV-2)|USS Lexington]]'' found in 2018.\n\nNavigation has long been a traditional human activity on the Coral Sea and there are 10 major ports on the Queensland coast alone. More than 3,500 ships operated in this area in 2007, making over 9,700 voyages that transported coal, sugar, iron ore, timber, oil, chemicals, cattle and other goods.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090912175345/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/40764/Ports_and_shipping.pdf Ports and shipping], Great Barrier Reef Outlook Report 2009</ref> The abundance of coral reefs hinders shipping traffic, and about 50\u201360 accidents per year were reported between 1990 and 2007 in the GBR alone.<ref name=\"GBRMPAshipping\">{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority |title=Shipping incidents in the Great Barrier Reef Marine Park |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/about_us/great_barrier_reef_outlook_report/outlook_report/evidence/01_standard_evidence_page220 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007214946/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/about_us/great_barrier_reef_outlook_report/outlook_report/evidence/01_standard_evidence_page220 |archivedate=7 October 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOther economic activities in the sea include fishing and exploration of petroleum deposits in the Gulf of Papua.<ref name=brit/> The sea is also a popular tourism destination. In 2006\u20132007, tourism on the GBR contributed A$5.1 billion to the Australian economy.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090912175408/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0004/40765/Tourism.pdf Tourism], Great Barrier Reef Outlook Report 2009</ref> The tourism is mostly foreign or from remote parts of Australia, with a local contribution of about A$153 million. In particular, about 14.6 million visits were made to the Coral Sea reefs by the Queensland residents over 12 months in 2008.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090912180323/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/41239/Recreation.pdf Recreation], Great Barrier Reef Outlook Report 2009</ref> Growing concerns over the environmental effects of tourism resulted in establishment in 1975 of the [[Great Barrier Reef Marine Park]]. There are also smaller state and national parks. In 1981, the Great Barrier Reef was declared a [[World Heritage Site]] by [[UNESCO]].<ref name=britGBR/> From the middle of 2004, approximately one-third of the GBR Marine Park is protected from species removal of any kind, including fishing, without written permission.<ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority|title=Marine Park Zoning|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/management/zoning/index.html|accessdate=8 August 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060719173858/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/management/zoning/index.html|archivedate=19 July 2006}}</ref>\n\nIt was suggested in 1923 that the Great Barrier Reef contains a major [[oil reservoir]]. After the ''Commonwealth Petroleum Search Subsidies Act'' of 1957, [[hydrocarbon exploration]] increased in Queensland, including a well drilled at [[Wreck Island (Queensland)|Wreck Island]] in the southern Great Barrier Reef in 1959.<ref name=Bowenoil>{{cite book\n| last      = Bowen|first = James\n|author2=Bowen, Margarita\n| title     = The Great Barrier Reef : history, science, heritage\n| year      = 2002\n| publisher = Cambridge : Cambridge University Press\n| isbn      = 0-521-82430-3\n| url       = https://books.google.com/?id=ywV16n6mOUUC&pg=PA262-IA331 |page=319}}</ref> In the 1960s, drilling for oil and gas was investigated throughout the Great Barrier Reef,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/1918/AR1976-1977.pdf |title=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority \u2013 Annual Report 1976-77 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608084150/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/1918/AR1976-1977.pdf |archivedate=8 June 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Australian Institute of Marine Science|year=1996|title=AIMS Science for Management of the Great Barrier Reef \u2013 The Great Barrier Reef at a Glance |url=http://www.aims.gov.au/pages/research/smgbr/smgbr10.html|accessdate=2006-11-10|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060825102818/http://www.aims.gov.au/pages/research/smgbr/smgbr10.html |archivedate=25 August 2006}}</ref> in the [[Torres Strait]], along \"the eastern seaboard of [[Cape York Peninsula|Cape York]] to [[Princess Charlotte Bay]]\" and along the coast from [[Cooktown]] to [[Fraser Island]]. In the late 1960s, more exploratory [[oil wells]] were drilled near Wreck Island in the Capricorn Channel, and near [[Darnley Island (Queensland)|Darnley Island]] in the Torres Strait, but with no results.<ref name=Bowenoil/> In the 1970s, responding to concern about [[oil spill]]s, the Australian government forbade petroleum drilling on the GBR.<ref name = 1975review>{{cite web|author=Department of the Environment and Heritage|title=Review of the Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Act 1975|url=http://www.deh.gov.au/coasts/publications/gbr-marine-park-act.html|accessdate=2006-11-02 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061018005108/http://deh.gov.au/coasts/publications/gbr-marine-park-act.html |archivedate = 18 October 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Parliament of Australia |year=2006 |title=Royal Commissions and Commissions of Inquiry |url=http://www.aph.gov.au/library/INTGUIDE/LAW/royalcommissions.htm |accessdate=2006-10-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107085441/http://www.aph.gov.au/library/INTGUIDE/LAW/royalcommissions.htm |archivedate=7 January 2011 }}</ref> Yet oil spills due to shipping accidents are still a threat to environment, with a total of 282 spills between 1987 and 2002.<ref name= waterquality>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority|year=2006|title=Principal water quality influences on Great Barrier Reef ecosystems|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/key_issues/water_quality/principal_influences.html|accessdate=2006-10-22|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061016155955/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/key_issues/water_quality/principal_influences.html|archivedate=16 October 2006}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Great barrier oil spill march 2010 (cropped).jpg|thumb|''Shen Neng 1'' aground on the Great Barrier Reef on 5 April 2010]]\nQueensland has several major urban centres on the coast including [[Cairns]], [[Townsville]], [[Mackay, Queensland|Mackay]], [[Rockhampton]], [[Bundaberg]], [[Sunshine Coast, Queensland|Sunshine Coast]] and the industrial city of [[Gladstone, Queensland|Gladstone]], which inevitably contaminate the sea. About thirty rivers and hundreds of small streams add continental water, which contains sediments, pesticides and industrial waste.<ref name=Henderson>{{cite journal|last=Henderson|first=Fiona|author2=Kroon, Frederike|year=2009|title=Overview of CSIRO Water Quality Research in the Great Barrier Reef, 2003\u20132008|publisher=[[CSIRO]]|url=http://www.csiro.au/files/files/przy.pdf|access-date=25 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022010556/http://csiro.au/files/files/przy.pdf|archive-date=22 October 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> Runoff is especially concerning in the region south of Cairns, as it may receive up to 4200 mm of rain per year.<ref name=meteo/> About 90% of sea contamination originates from land farming activities.<ref name=EPAQ>{{cite web|year=2003 |url=http://www.epa.qld.gov.au/register/p01258bs.pdf |title=Coastal water quality |work=The State of the Environment Report Queensland 2003 |publisher=Environment Protection Agency Queensland |format=PDF |accessdate=2007-06-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325201430/http://www.epa.qld.gov.au/register/p01258bs.pdf |archivedate=25 March 2009 }}</ref> The area is continuously urbanising, so that the population is expected to increase by 40% by 2026. As a result, 70\u201390% of the coastal wetlands has been lost over the past decades, and many remaining flora species are endangered.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090912180356/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0018/40761/coastal_development.pdf Coastal development], Great Barrier Reef Outlook Report 2009</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2010, the Chinese ship ''[[Shen Neng 1]]'' carrying 950 tonnes of oil, ran aground east of [[Rockhampton]] in [[Central Queensland]], Australia,<ref name=ABCnews>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/04/04/2863762.htm|title=Ship leaking oil 'way off course'|date=4 April 2010|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=4 April 2010}}</ref> causing the [[2010 Great Barrier Reef oil spill]] and inflicting the largest damage to the GBR and the Coral Sea so far.<ref name=\"abc2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/04/13/2871824.htm |title=Oil found on beach near damaged reef|date=13 April 2010|accessdate=13 April 2010|work=[[ABC News Online]]|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref> The scarred area was roughly {{Convert|3|km|mi|abbr=on}} long and {{Convert|250|m|ft|abbr=on}} wide,<ref name=\"Two men\">{{cite news|title=Two men in court over coal carrier grounding on Great Barrier Reef|author=AAP|newspaper =[[The Australian]]|date=15 April 2010|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/two-men-in-court-over-coal-carrier-grounding-on-great-barrier-reef/story-e6frg6oo-1225853950429|accessdate=15 April 2010|authorlink=Australian Associated Press}}</ref> and some parts of it have become completely devoid of marine life. There are concerns that there could be considerable long-term damage and it will take 10 to 20 years for the reef to recover.<ref>{{cite news|title=Great Barrier Reef island oil spill clean-up starts|author=AAP|author2=Andrew Fraser|newspaper=[[The Australian]]|date=14 April 2010|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/health-science/great-barrier-reef-island-oil-spill-clean-up-starts/story-e6frg8y6-1225853562627|accessdate=15 April 2010|authorlink=Australian Associated Press}}</ref> By 13 April 2010, [[Tarball (oil)|oil tar balls]] were washing up on the beaches of [[North West Island]], a significant bird [[rookery]] and turtle nesting colony.<ref name=\"abc2\"/>\n\nA group of 10 environment NGOs have come together as a coalition called the ''Protect our Coral Sea'' campaign, asking the government to create a very large highly protected Coral Sea Marine Park.<ref>[http://www.protectourcoralsea.org.au/ www.protectourcoralsea.org.au]. Retrieved on 2012-08-09.</ref> In November 2011 the Australian government announced that a {{convert|989842|km2|sqmi|0}} protected area was planned and pending approval.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-15889194 |title=Australia plans huge marine reserve in Coral Sea |work=BBC News |date=25 November 2011 |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Australia|Queensland}}\n*[[APNG (cable system)]]\n*[[Coral Sea Islands]]\n*[[Torres Strait Islands]]\n*[[Willis Island (Coral Sea)|Willis Island]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last = Hopley|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=omr72hD6dvQC|first = David |author2=Smithers, Scott G. |author3=Parnell, Kevin E.|title = The geomorphology of the Great Barrier Reef: development, diversity, and change|year = 2007|publisher = Cambridge University Press|isbn = 0-521-85302-8}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Coral Sea}}\n\n{{Interim Biogeographic Regionalisation for Australia (IBRA)}}\n{{List of Australian seas}}\n{{List of seas}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Australia\u2013New Caledonia border]]\n[[Category:Australia\u2013Solomon Islands border]]\n[[Category:Coral Sea| ]]\n[[Category:Marginal seas of the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Australia]]\n[[Category:Seas of Oceania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Short description|A marginal sea of the South Pacific off the northeast coast of Australia}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox sea\n| name = Coral Sea\n| image = Coral Sea map.png\n| caption = \n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = \n| coords = {{coord|18|S|158|E|type:waterbody_scale:10000000|display=inline,title}}\n| type = [[Sea]]\n| inflow = \n| outflow = \n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = [[Australia]], [[New Caledonia]] ([[France]]), [[Papua New Guinea]], [[Solomon Islands]], [[Vanuatu]]\n| length = \n| width = \n| area = {{convert|4791000|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth = {{convert|2394|m|abbr=on}}\n| max-depth = {{convert|9140|m|abbr=on}}\n| volume = {{convert|11470000|km3|acre.ft|abbr=on}}\n| frozen = \n| reference = <ref name=bse>[http://bse.sci-lib.com/article064525.html Coral Sea], [[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]] (in Russian)</ref><ref name=brit>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/137118/Coral-Sea Coral Sea], Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica on-line</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Coral Sea''' ({{Lang-fr|Mer de Corail}}) is a [[marginal sea]] of the [[Pacific Ocean|South Pacific]] off the northeast coast of [[Australia]], and classified as an [[Interim Biogeographic Regionalisation for Australia|interim Australian]] [[bioregion]]. The Coral Sea extends {{convert|2,000|km}} down the Australian northeast coast. The sea was the location for the [[Battle of the Coral Sea]], a major confrontation during [[World War II]] between the navies of the Empire of Japan, and the United States and Australia.\n\nThe sea contains numerous islands and [[coral reef|reef]]s, as well as the world's largest reef system, the [[Great Barrier Reef]] (GBR), which was declared a [[World Heritage Site]] by [[UNESCO]] in 1981. All previous [[oil exploration]] projects were terminated at the GBR in 1975, and fishing is restricted in many areas. The reefs and islands of the Coral Sea are particularly rich in birds and aquatic life and are a popular tourist destination, both nationally and internationally.\n\n==Geography==\nIt is bounded in the west by the east coast of [[Queensland]], thereby including the [[Great Barrier Reef]], in the east by [[Vanuatu]] (formerly the [[New Hebrides]]) and by [[New Caledonia]], and in the northeast approximately by the southern extremity of the [[Solomon Islands]]. In the northwest, it reaches to the south coast of eastern [[New Guinea]], thereby including the [[Gulf of Papua]]. It merges with the [[Tasman Sea]] in the south, with the [[Solomon Sea]] in the north and with the Pacific Ocean in the east. On the west, it is bounded by the mainland coast of [[Queensland]], and in the northwest, it connects with the [[Arafura Sea]] through the [[Torres Strait]].<ref name=brit/>\n\nThe sea is characterised by its warm and stable climate{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}, with frequent rains and [[tropical cyclone]]s\n\n==Extent==\n[[File:Coral Sea Islands.png|thumb|A map of the Coral Sea Islands]]\nWhile the [[Great Barrier Reef]] with its islands and cays belong to Queensland, most reefs and islets east of it are part of the [[Coral Sea Islands Territory]]. In addition, some islands west of and belonging to [[New Caledonia]] are also part of the Coral Sea Islands in a geographical sense, such as the [[Chesterfield Islands]] and [[Bellona Reefs]].\n\nThe [[International Hydrographic Organization]] defines the limits of the Coral Sea as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iho.int/iho_pubs/standard/S-23/S-23_Ed3_1953_EN.pdf|title=Limits of Oceans and Seas, 3rd edition|year=1953|publisher=[[International Hydrographic Organization]]|page=37|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref>\n<blockquote>\n''On the North.'' The South coast of [[New Guinea]] from the entrance to the [[Bensbach River]] (141\u00b001'E) to Gadogadoa Island near its Southeastern extreme ({{coord|10|38|S|150|34|E|display=inline}}), down this meridian to the 100 fathom line and thence along the Southern edges of Uluma Reef and those extending to the Eastward as far as the Southeast point of Lawik Reef ({{coord|11|43.5|S|153|56.5|E|display=inline}}) off Tagula Island, thence a line to the Southern extreme of [[Rennell Island]] ([[Solomon Islands]]) and from its Eastern point to Cape Surville, the Eastern extreme of San Cristobal Island <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Makira]]<nowiki>]</nowiki>, [[Solomon Islands|Solomons]]; thence through [[Nalongo and Nupani|Nupani Island]], the Northwestern of the [[Santa Cruz Islands]] ({{coord|10|04.5|S|165|40.5|E|display=inline}}) to the Northernmost Island of the [[Duff Islands]] ({{coord|9|48.5|S|167|06|E|display=inline}}).\n\n''On the Northeast.'' From the Northernmost island of the Duff Islands, through these islands to their Southeastern extreme, thence a line to M\u00e9r\u00e9 Lava, [[Vanuatu]] Islands({{coord|14|25|S|163|03|E|display=inline}}) and down the Eastern coasts of the islands of this Group to [[Anatom]] Island ({{coord|20|11|S|169|51|E|display=inline}}) in such a way that all the islands of these Groups, and the straits separating them, are included in the Coral Sea.\n\n''On the Southeast.'' A line from the Southeastern extreme of Anatom Island to Nokanhoui (reefs) ({{coord|22|46|S|167|34|E|display=inline}}) off the Southeast extreme of [[New Caledonia]], thence through the East point of [[Middleton Reef]] to the Eastern extreme of [[Elizabeth Reef]] ({{coord|29|55|S|159|02|E|display=inline}}) and down this meridian to [[30th parallel south|Latitude 30\u00b0 South]].\n\n''On the South.'' The parallel of 30\u00b0 South to the Australian coast.\n\n''On the West.'' The Eastern limit of the [[Arafura Sea]] [The entrance to the [[Bensbach River]] (141\u00b001'E), and thence a line to the Northwest extreme of [[Cape York Peninsula|York Peninsula]], Australia ({{coord|11|05|S|142|03|E|display=inline}})] and the East Coast of Australia as far south as Latitude 30\u00b0 South.\n</blockquote>\n\n==Geology==\nThe Coral Sea [[Oceanic basin|basin]] was formed between 58 million and 48 million years ago when the Queensland continental shelf was uplifted, forming the [[Great Dividing Range]], and continental blocks subsided at the same time.<ref>Hopley, p. 19</ref> The sea has been an important source of coral for the Great Barrier Reef, both during its formation and after [[sea level change|sea level lowering]].<ref>Hopley, p. 27</ref>\n\nThe geological formation processes are still proceeding, as partly evidenced by the [[seismic activity]]. Several hundred earthquakes with the [[Richter magnitude scale|magnitude]] between 2 and 6 were recorded in the period 1866\u20132000 along the Queensland coast and in the Coral Sea.<ref>Hopley, pp. 33\u201334</ref> On 2 April 2007, the Solomon Islands were struck by a [[2007 Solomon Islands earthquake and tsunami|major earthquake]] followed by a several metres tall [[tsunami]]. The epicentre of this magnitude 8.1 earthquake was {{convert|349|km|mi|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Honiara]], at a depth of {{convert|10|km|mi}}.<ref>[http://www.breakinglegalnews.com/entry/Solomon-Islands-earthquake-and-tsunami \"Solomon Islands earthquake and tsunami\"], Breaking Legal News \u2013 International, 4 March 2007</ref> It was followed by more than 44 aftershocks of a magnitude 5.0 or greater. The resulting tsunami killed at least 52 people and destroyed more than 900 homes.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6520461.stm \"Aid reaches tsunami-hit Solomons\"], ''BBC News'', 2007-04-03</ref>\n\nThe sea received its name because of its numerous coral formations. They include the GBR, which extends about {{convert|2000|km|mi|abbr=on}} along the northeast coast of Australia and includes approximately 2,900 individual reefs<ref name=britGBR>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/242906/Great-Barrier-Reef Great Barrier Reef], Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica on-line</ref> and 1000 islands.<ref>Hopley, pp. 1, 26</ref> The [[Chesterfield Islands]] and [[Lihou Reef National Nature Reserve|Lihou Reef]] are the largest [[atoll]]s of the Coral Sea.\n\n==Hydrology==\n[[File:East Australian Current.jpg|thumb|left|Thermal profile of the East Australian Current]]\nMajor Coral Sea currents form a counter-clockwise gyro which includes the [[East Australian Current]]. It brings warm nutrient-poor waters from the Coral Sea down the east coast of Australia to the cool waters of the Tasman Sea. This current is the strongest along the Australian coasts and transforms 30 million m<sup>3</sup>/s of water within a flow band of about 100 kilometres wide and 500 metres deep. The current is strongest around February and weakest around August.<ref>[http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/NaturalHazards/view.php?id=15366 East Australian Current], NASA</ref>\n\nThe major river flowing into the sea is the [[Burdekin River]], which has its delta southeast of [[Townsville]]. Owing to the seasonal and annual variations in occurrence of cyclones and in precipitation (typically between 200 and 1600 mm/year), its annual discharge can vary more than 10 times between the two succeeding years. In particular, in the period 1920\u20131999, the average flow rate near the delta was below 1000 m<sup>3</sup>/s in 1923, 1931, 1939, 1969, 1982, 1985, 1987, 1993 and 1995; it was above 25,000 m<sup>3</sup>/s in 1927, 1940, 1946, 1950, 1951, 1959, 1968, 1972, 1974 and 1991, and reached about 40,000 m<sup>3</sup>/s in 1946.<ref>Susan B. Marriott, Jan Alexander [https://books.google.com/books?id=jB2CKLZc2eMC&pg=PA31 Floodplains: interdisciplinary approaches], Geological Society, 1999 {{ISBN|1-86239-050-9}} p. 31</ref> This irregularity results in concomitant fluctuations of the sea water composition near the river delta.\n\nThe surface water temperature varies on the south of the sea from 19 \u00b0C in August to 24 \u00b0C in February. It is rather warm and stable at 27\u201328 \u00b0\u0421 in the north all through the year. Water salinity is 34.5\u201335.5\u2030 (parts per thousand).<ref name=bse/> The water is mostly very clear, with the visibility of about 30 metres (100 ft) near the reefs.<ref name=britGBR/>\n\n==Climate==\n[[File:Cyclone Larry 19 mar 2006 0025Z.jpg|thumb|[[Cyclone Larry|Tropical Cyclone Larry]] over the Great Barrier Reef, 19 March 2006]]\nThe sea has a subtropical climate and is frequently hit by [[tropical cyclone]]s, especially between January and April.<ref name=brit/> This range extends to November\u2013May in the areas south to 10\u00b0S. Between 1969 and 1997, the GBR experienced 80 cyclones, 90% which were of [[Saffir\u2013Simpson Hurricane Scale|category]] 1 or 2 (winds 17\u201333 m/s, central pressure 970\u20131000 hPa) and only 10% of category 3 (winds >33 m/s, pressure <970 hPa). The cyclone frequency decreased between 1997 and 2005 to 1.5 per year (12 in total).<ref name=h96>Hopley, p. 96</ref>\n\nAnnual rainfall typically ranges between 1,000 and 3,000 mm depending on the area. Most rains fall between December and March, in bursts of 30\u201360 days.<ref name=h96/> The number of clear days per year varies approximately between 80 and 125, and the typical temperature variation through the year are 18\u201327 \u00b0C.<ref name=meteo>[http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/data/ Climate Data Online], Australian Bureau of Meteorology</ref>\n\n[[global warming|Climate change]] made it 175 times more likely that the surface waters of the Coral Sea would reach the record-breaking temperatures March 2016 that bleached reefs, modeling analysis showed.<ref>{{cite web|author=John Upton |title=Climate Change is 'Devastating' The Great Barrier Reef |url=http://www.climatecentral.org/news/climate-change-devastating-great-barrier-reef--20295 |accessdate=2016-06-01}}</ref>\n\n===Winds===\nWinds in the Coral Sea can be classified by season, [[longitude]] and [[latitude]]. Southeasterly [[trade wind]]s dominate through all sea areas and all seasons, especially between 20\u00b0S and 25\u00b0S, west of the meridian of 155\u00b0E. However, between September and December they change to northerly and northwesterly winds in this region, and the direction is mostly southwestern in May\u2013August. West of 155\u00b0E, [[gale]]s are common between January and August and are less frequent in September\u2013December.<ref name=w/>\n\nIn January, the northwest [[monsoon]] may occur between the parallels of 15\u00b0S and 20\u00b0S, west of the 150\u00b0E meridian. Gales are rare in this region most of the year except for June\u2013August, when strong southeasterly winds occur a few days per month.<ref name=w/>\n\nThe southeasterly trades are also strong north of 15\u00b0S between March and November. They weaken and often change to westerly winds in December and to northerly and northwesterly winds in January\nand February.<ref name=w>[http://permanent.access.gpo.gov/websites/pollux/pollux.nss.nima.mil/NAV_PUBS/SD/pub127/127sec06.pdf Australia\u2014Coral Sea\u2014Islands and Dangers], p. 131</ref>\n\n==Flora==\nThe Australian shore of the Coral Sea is mostly composed of sand. The GBR is too far away to provide significant coral deposits, but it effectively screens the coast from the ocean waves. As a result, most land vegetation spreads down to the sea,<ref>Jonathan D. Sauer [https://books.google.com/books?id=EimtEIqbuGYC&pg=PA53 Cayman Islands seashore vegetation: a study in comparative biogeography], University of California Press, 1982 {{ISBN|0520096568}} pp. 47, 53</ref> and the coastal waters are rich in underwater vegetation, such as [[green algae]].<ref>Alan R. Longhurst [https://books.google.com/books?id=MFHK18F5aCsC&pg=PA332 Ecological Geography of the Sea], Academic Press, 1998 {{ISBN|0-12-455559-4}} pp. 331\u2013332</ref> The most common [[genus|genera]] of seagrasses are ''[[Halophila]]'' and ''[[Halodule]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/seagrasses |year=2005 |title=Environmental Status: Seagrasses |work=The State of the Great Barrier Reef Report \u2013 latest updates |accessdate=23 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323172107/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/seagrasses |archivedate=23 March 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe islands of the GBR contain more than 2,000 plant species, and three of these are [[Endemism|endemic]]. The northern islands have 300\u2013350 plant species which tend to be woody, whereas the southern islands have 200 which are more herbaceous; the Whitsunday region is the most diverse, supporting 1,141 species. The plants are spread by birds.<ref name=\"Flora and Fauna 5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora/appendix_05.html|title=Appendix 5- Island Flora and Fauna |year=2000|work=Fauna and Flora of the Great Barrier Reef World Heritage Area|accessdate=13 September 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070831160817/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora/appendix_05.html|archivedate=31 August 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Fauna==\n[[File:Coral Outcrop Flynn Reef.jpg|thumb|Corals on Flynn Reef near [[Cairns]]]]\n[[File:Crown of Thorns-jonhanson.jpg|thumb|Crown-of-thorns starfish]]\n[[File:Christmas Tree Worm.jpg|thumb|Christmas tree worm (''[[Spirobranchus giganteus]]'') in [[Porites]] coral. Admiralty, Osprey Reef]]\n[[File:Laticauda colubrina (Wakatobi).jpg|thumb|A banded [[Laticauda|sea krait]] ''Laticauda colubrina'']]\n\nThe sea hosts numerous species of [[Sea anemone|anemones]], [[sponge]]s, worms (e.g. ''[[Spirobranchus giganteus]]'' shown in the photograph), [[Gastropoda|gastropods]], [[lobster]]s, [[crayfish]], [[prawn]]s and crabs. [[Red algae]] ''[[Lithothamnion]]'' and ''[[Porolithon]]'' colour many coral reefs purple-red and the [[green alga]] ''[[Halimeda]]'' is found throughout the sea. The coastal plants consisting of only about 30\u201340 species, and [[mangrove]]s occur in the northern part of the sea.<ref name=britGBR/> Four hundred coral species, both [[hard coral]]s and [[soft coral]]s inhabit the reefs.<ref name=\"CRC species\"/> The majority of these spawn [[gamete]]s, breeding in [[mass spawning]] events that are triggered by the rising sea temperatures of spring and summer, the lunar cycle, and the diurnal cycle. Reefs in the inner GBR spawn during the week after the full moon in October, while the outer reefs spawn in November and December.<ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority |year=2006 |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/8879/Fact_Sheet_20_Coral_Spawning.pdf |title=Information Fact Sheets No. 20 Coral Spawning |format=PDF |accessdate=27 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704074131/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/8879/Fact_Sheet_20_Coral_Spawning.pdf |archivedate=4 July 2009 }}</ref> Its common soft corals belong to 36 genera.<ref>{{cite web |author=Australian Institute of Marine Science |year=2002 |url=http://www.aims.gov.au/pages/research/soft-corals/soft-corals00.html|title=Soft coral atlas of the Great Barrier Reef|accessdate=27 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070406051711/http://www.aims.gov.au/pages/research/soft-corals/soft-corals00.html |archivedate=6 April 2007}}</ref> There are more than 1500 [[List of fishes of the Coral Sea|fish species]] in the reef systems.<ref>C.Michael Hogan. 2011. [http://www.eoearth.org/article/Coral_Sea?topic=49523 ''Coral Sea''. Encyclopedia of Earth. Eds. P.Saundry & C.J.Cleveland. National Council for Science and the Environment. Washington DC]</ref> Five hundred species of marine algae or [[seaweed]] live on the reef,<ref name=\"CRC species\"/> including thirteen species of the genus ''[[Halimeda]]'', which deposit [[calcareous]] mounds up to {{convert|100|m|yd}} wide, creating mini-[[ecosystem]]s on their surface which have been compared to [[rainforest]] cover.<ref>Hopley, p. 185</ref>\n\nCrown-of-thorns starfish (''[[Acanthaster planci]]'') is the major predator of the reefs, as it preys upon [[coral polyp]]s by climbing onto them, [[wiktionary:extrude|extruding]] its stomach over them, and releasing [[digestive enzyme]]s to absorb the liquefied tissue. An individual adult can eat up to 6 m<sup>2</sup> of reef per year.<ref>{{cite web|author=Pierre Madl|title=Marine Biology I \u2013 Acanthaster planci| url=http://biophysics.sbg.ac.at/planci/planci.htm| accessdate=2006-08-28}}</ref> In 2000, an outbreak<ref>The CRC Reef Research Centre defines an outbreak as when there are more than 30 adult starfish in an area of one hectare. {{cite web|author=CRC Reef Research Centre|title=Managing crown-of-thorns starfish outbreaks|url=http://www.reef.crc.org.au/discover/plantsanimals/cots/cotsmanage.html|accessdate=2006-10-18|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002033140/http://www.reef.crc.org.au//discover/plantsanimals/cots/cotsmanage.html|archivedate=2 October 2006|df=dmy-all}} (PDF)</ref> of crown-of-thorns starfish contributed to a loss of 66% of live coral cover on sampled reefs.<ref name=\"cots 1999-2000\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reef.crc.org.au/publications/techreport/techrept32.htm|title=Crc Reef Research Centre Technical Report No. 32 \u2013 Crown-of-thorns starfish(Acanthaster planci) in the central GBR region. Results of fine-scale surveys conducted in 1999\u20132000.|accessdate=2007-06-07|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070829092853/http://www.reef.crc.org.au/publications/techreport/techrept32.htm|archivedate=29 August 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Changes in water quality and [[overfishing]] of natural predators, such as the [[Triton (mollusk)|giant Triton]], may have contributed to an increase in the number of crown-of-thorns starfish.<ref>{{cite web|author=CRC Reef Research Centre |title=Crown-of-thorns starfish on the Great Barrier Reef |url=http://www.reef.crc.org.au/publications/brochures/COTS_web_Nov2003.pdf |accessdate=2006-08-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060826192429/http://www.reef.crc.org.au//publications/brochures/COTS_web_Nov2003.pdf |archivedate=26 August 2006 |df=dmy }} (PDF)</ref>\n\nThere are at least 30 species of whales, dolphins, and [[porpoises]], including the [[dwarf minke whale]], [[Indo-Pacific humpback dolphin]], [[humpback whale]] and [[dugong]]s.<ref name=\"CRC species\">{{cite web|author=CRC Reef Research Centre Ltd |title=Reef facts: Plants and Animals on the Great Barrier Reef |url=http://www.reef.crc.org.au/discover/plantsanimals/facts_plantanimal.htm |accessdate=14 July 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060821194423/http://www.reef.crc.org.au/discover/plantsanimals/facts_plantanimal.htm |archivedate=21 August 2006 |df=dmy}}</ref><ref name=\"GBRMPA Fauna and Flora\">{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority|year=2000 |title=Fauna and Flora of the Great Barrier Reef World Heritage Area|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora |accessdate=24 November 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061014182747/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora |archivedate=14 October 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/marine_mammals |year=2004 |title=Environmental Status: Marine Mammals |work=The State of the Great Barrier Reef Report \u2013 latest updates |accessdate=13 March 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619132323/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/marine_mammals |archivedate=19 June 2010}}</ref> Six species of [[sea turtle]]s breed on the GBR \u2013 the [[green sea turtle]], [[leatherback sea turtle]], [[hawksbill turtle]], [[loggerhead sea turtle]], [[flatback turtle]] and the [[olive ridley]].<ref name=\"rap turtle dugong\">{{cite book |last= Dobbs |first= Kirstin |title= Marine turtle and dugong habitats in the Great Barrier Reef Marine Park used to implement biophysical operational principles for the Representative Areas Program |publisher=Great Barrier Marine Park Authority |year= 2007 |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/18799/rap_turtle_and_dugong_bop.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704064222/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/18799/rap_turtle_and_dugong_bop.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2009-07-04}}</ref>\n\nMore than 200 species of birds (including 22 species of seabirds and 32 species of shorebirds) visit, nest or roost on the islands and reefs,<ref>Hopley, pp. 450\u2013451</ref> including the [[white-bellied sea eagle]] and [[roseate tern]].<ref name=\"CRC species\"/> Most nesting sites are on islands in the northern and southern regions of the GBR, with 1.4\u20131.7 million birds using the sites to breed.<ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/seabirds/ |title=Environmental status: birds |work=The State of the Great Barrier Reef Report \u2013 latest updates |accessdate=23 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090613210510/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/seabirds/ |archivedate=13 June 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/seabirds/condition |title=Environmental status: birds Condition |work=The State of the Great Barrier Reef Report \u2013 latest updates |accessdate=23 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100416181445/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/seabirds/condition |archivedate=16 April 2010 }}</ref>\n\nSeventeen species of [[sea snake]], including ''[[Laticauda colubrina]]''<ref>[http://reptile-database.reptarium.cz/species.php?genus=Laticauda&species=colubrina Laticauda colubrina (SCHNEIDER, 1799)], The Reptile Database</ref> (pictured), live on the GBR in warm waters up to {{convert|50|m|ft}} deep and are more common in the southern than in the northern section; none of them are endemic or endangered.<ref name=\"Flora and Fauna 2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora/appendix_02.html |year=2000 |title=Appendix 2 \u2013 Listed Marine Species |work=Fauna and Flora of the Great Barrier Reef World Heritage Area |accessdate=23 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100326152229/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora/appendix_02.html |archivedate=26 March 2010 }}</ref> The venom of many of these snakes is highly toxic; for example, ''[[Aipysurus duboisii]]'' is regarded as the world's most venomous sea snake.<ref>P. Gopalakrishnakone [https://books.google.com/books?id=i2yTrfdnnq8C&pg=PA98 Sea snake toxinology], NUS Press, 1994, {{ISBN|9971-69-193-0}} p. 98</ref><ref>Harold Heatwole [https://books.google.com/books?id=80ERtB6qgGgC&pg=PT127 Sea Snakes], UNSW Press, 1999, {{ISBN|0-86840-776-3}} p. 115</ref><ref>Steve Backshall [https://books.google.com/books?id=qOyV7KnJRCYC&pg=PA155 Steve Backshall's venom: poisonous animals in the natural world], New Holland Publishers, 2007, {{ISBN|1-84537-734-6}} p. 155</ref>\n\nThere are more than 1,500 [[List of fishes of the Coral Sea|fish species]], including the clownfish ([[Amphiprioninae]]), red bass (''[[Lutjanus bohar]]''), red-throat emperor (''[[Lethrinus miniatus]]''), [[coral trout]] (''[[Plectropomus leopardus]]'') and several species of snapper ([[Lutjanidae]]).<ref name=\"CRC species\"/> Forty-nine species [[Reproductive synchrony|mass spawn]] and eighty-four other species spawn elsewhere in their range.<ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/key_issues/fisheries/spawning_sites|title=Fish Spawning Aggregation Sites on the Great Barrier Reef|accessdate=14 March 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216133142/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/key_issues/fisheries/spawning_sites|archivedate=16 December 2008}}</ref> With a maximum total length of 0.84 cm (0.33 in), ''[[Schindleria brevipinguis]]'', which is native to the GBR and Osprey Reef, is one of the smallest known fish and vertebrate.<ref>W. Watson and H.J. Walker Jr, [http://www.amonline.net.au/pdf/publications/1429_complete.pdf ''The World\u2019s Smallest Vertebrate, Schindleria brevipinguis, A New Paedomorphic Species in the Family Schindleriidae (Perciformes: Gobioidei)''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080808034959/http://www.amonline.net.au/pdf/publications/1429_complete.pdf |date=8 August 2008 }} Records of the Australian Museum (2004) Vol. 56: 139\u2013142. However, it was claimed later (2006) that ''[[Paedocypris progenetica]]'' is the smallest fish and vertebrate.</ref> There are at least 330 species of [[ascidian]]s on the reef system with the diameter of {{convert|1|-|10|cm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}}. Between 300 and 500 species of [[bryozoan]]s live on the reef.<ref name=\"Flora and Fauna 4\"/>\n\n[[Saltwater crocodile]]s live in [[mangrove]] and [[salt marsh]]es on the coast.<ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority |year=2005 |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/marine_reptiles |title=Environmental Status: Marine Reptiles |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701120436/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/marine_reptiles |archivedate=1 July 2010 }}</ref> Around 125 species of [[shark]], [[stingray]], [[Skate (fish)|skate]]s or [[chimaera]] live on the GBR,<ref name=\"Flora and Fauna 4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora/appendix_04.html|title=Appendix 4- Other species of conservation concern |year=2000|work=Fauna and Flora of the Great Barrier Reef World Heritage Area|accessdate=13 September 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070831155453/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/misc_pub/fauna_flora/appendix_04.html|archivedate=31 August 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/sharks_rays|title=Environmental Status: Sharks and rays|work=The State of the Great Barrier Reef Report \u2013 latest updates|accessdate=23 May 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070329002717/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/info_services/publications/sotr/latest_updates/sharks_rays|archivedate=29 March 2007}}</ref> in addition to about 5,000 species of [[mollusc]]. The latter include the [[giant clam]] and various [[nudibranch]]s and [[cone snail]]s.<ref name=\"CRC species\"/>\n\nOne study of 443 individual sharks gives the following distribution of their species on the Australian side of the Coral Sea: grey reef shark (''[[Carcharhinus amblyrhynchos]]'', 69%), whitetip reef shark (''[[Triaenodon obesus]]'', 21%), silvertip shark (''[[Carcharhinus albimarginatus]]'', 10%), tiger shark (''[[Galeocerdo cuvier]]'', <1%) and great hammerhead (''[[Sphyrna mokarran]]'', <1%). The interaction rate (free diving) at the Coral Sea reefs ranged from a few to 26 sharks per\nhour.<ref>Australian Underwater Federation. [http://www.auf-spearfishing.com.au/Documentation/Coral%20Sea%20Shark%20Report%202008-7.pdf \"Community monitoring of reef sharks in the Coral Sea and Great Barrier Reef, Australia\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080627115546/http://www.auf-spearfishing.com.au/Documentation/Coral%20Sea%20Shark%20Report%202008-7.pdf |date=27 June 2008 }} (2008)</ref> The rare ''[[Etmopterus dislineatus]]'' shark species is endemic to the central part of the Coral Sea. It has been observed at depths of 590\u2013700 m on or near the [[continental slope]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=izASW0ydfVAC&pg=PA374 Deep Sea 2003: conference on the governance and management of deep-sea fisheries], Food & Agriculture Org., 2006 {{ISBN|92-5-105457-6}} p. 374</ref>\n\n==Human activities==\nThe coastal areas of the Coral Sea were populated at least 40,000 years ago by prehistoric people descending through the northern islands. Those Aboriginal tribes have been dispersed and nowadays only about 70 groups live in the area around the GBR.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090912175845/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0012/41241/Traditional_Use.pdf Traditional Use], Great Barrier Reef Outlook Report 2009</ref>\n\nThe sea was the location for the [[Battle of the Coral Sea]], a major confrontation during [[World War II]] between the navies of the [[Empire of Japan]], and the United States and Australia. An example is the wreckage of the ''[[USS Lexington (CV-2)|USS Lexington]]'' found in 2018.\n\nNavigation has long been a traditional human activity on the Coral Sea and there are 10 major ports on the Queensland coast alone. More than 3,500 ships operated in this area in 2007, making over 9,700 voyages that transported coal, sugar, iron ore, timber, oil, chemicals, cattle and other goods.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090912175345/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/40764/Ports_and_shipping.pdf Ports and shipping], Great Barrier Reef Outlook Report 2009</ref> The abundance of coral reefs hinders shipping traffic, and about 50\u201360 accidents per year were reported between 1990 and 2007 in the GBR alone.<ref name=\"GBRMPAshipping\">{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority |title=Shipping incidents in the Great Barrier Reef Marine Park |url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/about_us/great_barrier_reef_outlook_report/outlook_report/evidence/01_standard_evidence_page220 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007214946/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/about_us/great_barrier_reef_outlook_report/outlook_report/evidence/01_standard_evidence_page220 |archivedate=7 October 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOther economic activities in the sea include fishing and exploration of petroleum deposits in the Gulf of Papua.<ref name=brit/> The sea is also a popular tourism destination. In 2006\u20132007, tourism on the GBR contributed A$5.1 billion to the Australian economy.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090912175408/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0004/40765/Tourism.pdf Tourism], Great Barrier Reef Outlook Report 2009</ref> The tourism is mostly foreign or from remote parts of Australia, with a local contribution of about A$153 million. In particular, about 14.6 million visits were made to the Coral Sea reefs by the Queensland residents over 12 months in 2008.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090912180323/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/41239/Recreation.pdf Recreation], Great Barrier Reef Outlook Report 2009</ref> Growing concerns over the environmental effects of tourism resulted in establishment in 1975 of the [[Great Barrier Reef Marine Park]]. There are also smaller state and national parks. In 1981, the Great Barrier Reef was declared a [[World Heritage Site]] by [[UNESCO]].<ref name=britGBR/> From the middle of 2004, approximately one-third of the GBR Marine Park is protected from species removal of any kind, including fishing, without written permission.<ref>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority|title=Marine Park Zoning|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/management/zoning/index.html|accessdate=8 August 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060719173858/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/management/zoning/index.html|archivedate=19 July 2006}}</ref>\n\nIt was suggested in 1923 that the Great Barrier Reef contains a major [[oil reservoir]]. After the ''Commonwealth Petroleum Search Subsidies Act'' of 1957, [[hydrocarbon exploration]] increased in Queensland, including a well drilled at [[Wreck Island (Queensland)|Wreck Island]] in the southern Great Barrier Reef in 1959.<ref name=Bowenoil>{{cite book\n| last      = Bowen|first = James\n|author2=Bowen, Margarita\n| title     = The Great Barrier Reef : history, science, heritage\n| year      = 2002\n| publisher = Cambridge : Cambridge University Press\n| isbn      = 0-521-82430-3\n| url       = https://books.google.com/?id=ywV16n6mOUUC&pg=PA262-IA331 |page=319}}</ref> In the 1960s, drilling for oil and gas was investigated throughout the Great Barrier Reef,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/1918/AR1976-1977.pdf |title=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority \u2013 Annual Report 1976-77 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608084150/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/1918/AR1976-1977.pdf |archivedate=8 June 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Australian Institute of Marine Science|year=1996|title=AIMS Science for Management of the Great Barrier Reef \u2013 The Great Barrier Reef at a Glance |url=http://www.aims.gov.au/pages/research/smgbr/smgbr10.html|accessdate=2006-11-10|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060825102818/http://www.aims.gov.au/pages/research/smgbr/smgbr10.html |archivedate=25 August 2006}}</ref> in the [[Torres Strait]], along \"the eastern seaboard of [[Cape York Peninsula|Cape York]] to [[Princess Charlotte Bay]]\" and along the coast from [[Cooktown]] to [[Fraser Island]]. In the late 1960s, more exploratory [[oil wells]] were drilled near Wreck Island in the Capricorn Channel, and near [[Darnley Island (Queensland)|Darnley Island]] in the Torres Strait, but with no results.<ref name=Bowenoil/> In the 1970s, responding to concern about [[oil spill]]s, the Australian government forbade petroleum drilling on the GBR.<ref name = 1975review>{{cite web|author=Department of the Environment and Heritage|title=Review of the Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Act 1975|url=http://www.deh.gov.au/coasts/publications/gbr-marine-park-act.html|accessdate=2006-11-02 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061018005108/http://deh.gov.au/coasts/publications/gbr-marine-park-act.html |archivedate = 18 October 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Parliament of Australia |year=2006 |title=Royal Commissions and Commissions of Inquiry |url=http://www.aph.gov.au/library/INTGUIDE/LAW/royalcommissions.htm |accessdate=2006-10-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107085441/http://www.aph.gov.au/library/INTGUIDE/LAW/royalcommissions.htm |archivedate=7 January 2011 }}</ref> Yet oil spills due to shipping accidents are still a threat to environment, with a total of 282 spills between 1987 and 2002.<ref name= waterquality>{{cite web|author=Great Barrier Reef Marine Park Authority|year=2006|title=Principal water quality influences on Great Barrier Reef ecosystems|url=http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/key_issues/water_quality/principal_influences.html|accessdate=2006-10-22|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061016155955/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/corp_site/key_issues/water_quality/principal_influences.html|archivedate=16 October 2006}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Great barrier oil spill march 2010 (cropped).jpg|thumb|''Shen Neng 1'' aground on the Great Barrier Reef on 5 April 2010]]\nQueensland has several major urban centres on the coast including [[Cairns]], [[Townsville]], [[Mackay, Queensland|Mackay]], [[Rockhampton]], [[Bundaberg]], [[Sunshine Coast, Queensland|Sunshine Coast]] and the industrial city of [[Gladstone, Queensland|Gladstone]], which inevitably contaminate the sea. About thirty rivers and hundreds of small streams add continental water, which contains sediments, pesticides and industrial waste.<ref name=Henderson>{{cite journal|last=Henderson|first=Fiona|author2=Kroon, Frederike|year=2009|title=Overview of CSIRO Water Quality Research in the Great Barrier Reef, 2003\u20132008|publisher=[[CSIRO]]|url=http://www.csiro.au/files/files/przy.pdf|access-date=25 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022010556/http://csiro.au/files/files/przy.pdf|archive-date=22 October 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> Runoff is especially concerning in the region south of Cairns, as it may receive up to 4200 mm of rain per year.<ref name=meteo/> About 90% of sea contamination originates from land farming activities.<ref name=EPAQ>{{cite web|year=2003 |url=http://www.epa.qld.gov.au/register/p01258bs.pdf |title=Coastal water quality |work=The State of the Environment Report Queensland 2003 |publisher=Environment Protection Agency Queensland |format=PDF |accessdate=2007-06-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325201430/http://www.epa.qld.gov.au/register/p01258bs.pdf |archivedate=25 March 2009 }}</ref> The area is continuously urbanising, so that the population is expected to increase by 40% by 2026. As a result, 70\u201390% of the coastal wetlands has been lost over the past decades, and many remaining flora species are endangered.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090912180356/http://www.gbrmpa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0018/40761/coastal_development.pdf Coastal development], Great Barrier Reef Outlook Report 2009</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2010, the Chinese ship ''[[Shen Neng 1]]'' carrying 950 tonnes of oil, ran aground east of [[Rockhampton]] in [[Central Queensland]], Australia,<ref name=ABCnews>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/04/04/2863762.htm|title=Ship leaking oil 'way off course'|date=4 April 2010|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=4 April 2010}}</ref> causing the [[2010 Great Barrier Reef oil spill]] and inflicting the largest damage to the GBR and the Coral Sea so far.<ref name=\"abc2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/04/13/2871824.htm |title=Oil found on beach near damaged reef|date=13 April 2010|accessdate=13 April 2010|work=[[ABC News Online]]|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref> The scarred area was roughly {{Convert|3|km|mi|abbr=on}} long and {{Convert|250|m|ft|abbr=on}} wide,<ref name=\"Two men\">{{cite news|title=Two men in court over coal carrier grounding on Great Barrier Reef|author=AAP|newspaper =[[The Australian]]|date=15 April 2010|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/two-men-in-court-over-coal-carrier-grounding-on-great-barrier-reef/story-e6frg6oo-1225853950429|accessdate=15 April 2010|authorlink=Australian Associated Press}}</ref> and some parts of it have become completely devoid of marine life. There are concerns that there could be considerable long-term damage and it will take 10 to 20 years for the reef to recover.<ref>{{cite news|title=Great Barrier Reef island oil spill clean-up starts|author=AAP|author2=Andrew Fraser|newspaper=[[The Australian]]|date=14 April 2010|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/health-science/great-barrier-reef-island-oil-spill-clean-up-starts/story-e6frg8y6-1225853562627|accessdate=15 April 2010|authorlink=Australian Associated Press}}</ref> By 13 April 2010, [[Tarball (oil)|oil tar balls]] were washing up on the beaches of [[North West Island]], a significant bird [[rookery]] and turtle nesting colony.<ref name=\"abc2\"/>\n\nA group of 10 environment NGOs have come together as a coalition called the ''Protect our Coral Sea'' campaign, asking the government to create a very large highly protected Coral Sea Marine Park.<ref>[http://www.protectourcoralsea.org.au/ www.protectourcoralsea.org.au]. Retrieved on 2012-08-09.</ref> In November 2011 the Australian government announced that a {{convert|989842|km2|sqmi|0}} protected area was planned and pending approval.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-15889194 |title=Australia plans huge marine reserve in Coral Sea |work=BBC News |date=25 November 2011 |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Australia|Queensland}}\n*[[APNG (cable system)]]\n*[[Coral Sea Islands]]\n*[[Torres Strait Islands]]\n*[[Willis Island (Coral Sea)|Willis Island]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last = Hopley|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=omr72hD6dvQC|first = David |author2=Smithers, Scott G. |author3=Parnell, Kevin E.|title = The geomorphology of the Great Barrier Reef: development, diversity, and change|year = 2007|publisher = Cambridge University Press|isbn = 0-521-85302-8}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Coral Sea}}\n\n{{Interim Biogeographic Regionalisation for Australia (IBRA)}}\n{{List of Australian seas}}\n{{List of seas}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Australia\u2013New Caledonia border]]\n[[Category:Australia\u2013Solomon Islands border]]\n[[Category:Coral Sea| ]]\n[[Category:Marginal seas of the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Australia]]\n[[Category:Seas of Oceania]]\n", "name_user": "2601:c6:c880:3480:712a:3f31:b6ce:b2c3", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(sea to water)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coral_Sea"}
{"title_page": "2020\u201321 Tulsa Golden Hurricane men's basketball team", "text_new": "{{short description|University of Tulsa NCAA team}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |mode=Basketball\n  |year=2020\u201321\n  |prev_year=2019\u201320\n  |next_year=2021\u201322\n  |team=Tulsa Golden Hurricane\n  |image=Tulsa Golden Hurricane wordmark.svg\n  |image_size=175\n  |conference=American Athletic Conference\n  |division=\n  |short_conf=AAC\n  |CoachRank=\n  |APRank=\n  |record=\n  |conf_record=\n  |head_coach=[[Frank Haith]]\n  |hc_year = 7th\n  |asst_coach1=[[Jerry Wainwright]]\n  |asst_coach2=Kwanza Johnson\n  |asst_coach3=[[Shea Seals]]\n  |stadium=[[Reynolds Center]]\n  |champion=\n}}\n{{2020\u201321 American Athletic Conference men's basketball standings}}\nThe '''2020\u201321 Tulsa Golden Hurricane men's basketball team''' will represent the [[University of Tulsa]] during the [[2020\u201321 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]]. The Golden Hurricane, led by seventh-year head coach [[Frank Haith]], plays their home games at the [[Reynolds Center]] in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]] as members of the [[American Athletic Conference]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.collegesportsmadness.com/article/17640|title=#105 Tulsa Men's Basketball 2019\u20132020 Preview|website=www.collegesportsmadness.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref>\n\n==Previous season==\nThe [[2019\u201320 Tulsa Golden Hurricane men's basketball team|Golden Hurricane]] finished the [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2019\u201320 season]] 21\u201310, 13\u20135 in [[2019\u201320 American Athletic Conference men's basketball season|AAC play]] to finish in a tie for first place and winning a share of the regular season title. Coach Haith would go on to be honored as [[American Athletic Conference Men's Basketball Coach of the Year]] for the season. They entered as the No. 3 seed in the [[2020 American Athletic Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|AAC Tournament]], which was ultimately cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n==Offseason==\n===Departures===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n! Name !! Number !! Pos. !! Height !! Weight !! Year !! Hometown !! class=\"unsortable\" | Reason for departure\n|-\n| Martins Igbanu || 1 || F || 6'8\" || 235 || {{sort|4|Senior}} || [[Lagos|Lagos, Nigeria]] || Graduated\n|-\n| Isaiah Hill || 4 || G || 6'0\" || 165 || {{sort|1|Freshman}} || [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield, CA]] || Transferred to [[Fresno State Bulldogs men's basketball|Fresno State]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Jackson |title=Bakersfield star Isaiah Hill transferring home to Fresno State |url=https://247sports.com/college/fresno-state/Article/Bakersfield-star-Isaiah-Hill-transferring-home-to-Fresno-State-basketball-145590191/ |website=247sports.com |accessdate=11 Apr 2020 |date=31 Mar 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| Lawson Korita || 5 || G || 6'5\" || 205 || {{sort|4|Senior}} || [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock, AR]] || Graduated\n|-\n| Reggie Jones || 22 || G || 6'6\" || 210 || {{sort|3|Sophomore}} || [[Marion, Indiana|Marion, IN]] || Transferred to [[Ball State Cardinals men's basketball|Ball State]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Tribune sports staff |title=Ball State men's basketball adds 2 transfers |url=https://www.kokomotribune.com/sports/ball-state-mens-basketball-adds-2-transfers/article_75c76822-7f59-11ea-b8cd-23fbad025f12.html |accessdate=15 Apr 2020 |work=[[Kokomo Tribune]] |date=20 Apr 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Zeke Moore (basketball)|Zeke Moore]] || 23 || G || 6'7\" || 210 || {{sort|2.5|RS Sophomore}} || [[St. Louis|St. Louis, MO]] || Transferred to [[SIU Edwardsville Cougars men's basketball|SIU Edwardsville]] (mid-season).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hines |first1=Kelly |title=TU guard Moore leaving men's basketball program |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/sports/college/tu/tu-guard-moore-leaving-men-s-basketball-program/article_754b1028-8101-5c8e-b010-89ec19e240b6.html |accessdate